18
00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:20.385
how it's expanded into
sonata-allegro form.

19
00:01:20.385 --> 00:01:24.620
Sonata-allegro form as you can see,

20
00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:28.850
like ternary form has three parts,
exposition, development, recap.

21
00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:32.030
Home, away, home.

22
00:01:32.030 --> 00:01:34.760
First theme in the exposition.

23
00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:37.760
Within that exposition
the first theme then moves

24
00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.910
by means of a transition that
modulates to a new second theme and

25
00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:46.840
then ultimately a closing theme,
that exposition can be repeated.

26
00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:49.310
Then we go on to the development section.

27
00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:52.190
In the development sections,
almost anything goes.

28
00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:53.810
The theme can be varied.

29
00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:57.420
It can be taken apart,
decomposed, if you will.

30
00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:01.980
It can be reassembled in
imaginative sorts of ways.

31
00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:07.000
Generally speaking with regard to texture,
we'll have more polyphony

32
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.470
